# PeerPoint is a peer counselling platform for Strathmore University where trained student peer counsellors provide support to fellow students under administrative oversight.
## Context
PeerPoint is a peer counselling platform for Strathmore University. This is the frontend-only phase: mock auth, no backend calls, realistic placeholder data only. The goal is a clean, demoable UI — not a finished product.

## Tech Stack
- Vite + React 18
- React Router v6
- Tailwind CSS
- React Context for state (no Redux/Zustand/other state libs)
- lucide-react for all icons (no inline SVGs unless lucide doesn't have the icon)
- One component per file

## Folder Structure
```
src/
├── components/   (shared UI: Button, Card, Badge, Input, CrisisSupportCard, etc.)
├── context/      (AuthContext.jsx)
├── data/         (mock data files)
├── layouts/      (PublicLayout, DashboardLayout)
├── pages/        (actual screens — Landing, Login, Signup, dashboards, etc.)
├── routes/       (AppRouter.jsx, ProtectedRoute.jsx — routing config only, no screens here)
├── App.jsx
├── main.jsx
└── index.css
```

## Design Tokens (registered in tailwind.config.js theme.extend.colors)
- primary: #2D7D8A
- primary-dark: #006470
- background: #F8F6F2
- dark-surface: #1E2A35
- success: #10B981
- warning: #F59E0B
- danger: #EF4444
- crisis: #CC0000
- crisis-light: #FFDAD4

## CRITICAL COLOR RULE
`crisis` and `crisis-light` exist ONLY for the CrisisSupportCard component (the 24/7 emergency helpline card seen on student/counsellor dashboards). Never use `crisis` colors for buttons, nav items, badges, links, active states, or anything else anywhere in the app. If something needs urgent/error styling outside the crisis card, use `danger`, not `crisis`. This is a hard rule, not a style suggestion.

## Typography
- Headings: `font-heading` → Plus Jakarta Sans
- Body: `font-body` → Work Sans
- Both loaded via Google Fonts `<link>` tags in `index.html`, and mapped in `tailwind.config.js` under `theme.extend.fontFamily`.

## Visual Style
Calm, trustworthy, soft, student-friendly, modern. Generous spacing, rounded corners (`rounded-xl` / `rounded-2xl`), layered cards, soft shadows, subtle gradients where tasteful. Avoid sharp corners, dense enterprise-SaaS layouts, or default Bootstrap-looking components.

## Interactions (required on all interactive elements)
- Buttons: hover → `scale(1.02)` + `translateY(-2px)`, smooth transition
- Cards: subtle lift/shadow increase on hover
- Inputs: animated focus state with a visible focus ring
- No static, lifeless interfaces

## Auth (real API for login/signup; mock data elsewhere)

Login and signup call the FastAPI backend (`VITE_API_URL`). Bearer tokens are stored in `localStorage` as `access_token`; the user object is stored as `peerpoint_user`.

User shape:

```js
{
  id,
  fullName,
  email,
  role: "student" | "counsellor" | "admin",  // cosmetic fallback label only — DO NOT route on it
  roles: ["student", ...],                   // all active roles from API (source of truth for access)
  isVerified
}
```

Protected routes accept any role listed in `user.roles` (dual student+counsellor accounts can access both portals).

### Multi-role portal picker (Prompt 5)

Dual/triple-role users **pick which portal shell they wear** and can switch anytime.
This is **client-side only** — it never changes what the API authorizes (always the
full `user.roles[]`), and is **not** the DB `users.role` column.

- `AuthContext` exposes `activePortal`, `availablePortals` (student always; counsellor
  only when `isVerified`; admin always), `setActivePortal`, and `switchPortal`.
- The active portal is persisted as `peerpoint_active_portal` (last-used wins on return).
- After login/signup, `resolvePostAuthRedirect` sends multi-portal users to
  `/choose-portal` (unless a valid portal is already stored), single-portal users
  straight to their home, and zero-portal users to the backend `redirect_to`.
- `PortalSwitcher` in both layouts lets users hop between shells; each shell syncs
  `activePortal` to its route (route wins over stale storage).
- Route on `activePortal` / `user.roles`, **never** on `resolvePrimaryRole` priority
  (which would wrongly pick "student" while browsing `/counsellor`).

**Wired to API (Prompts 3–9):** auth, counsellor directory, counsellor profile, session booking, student/counsellor session flows, dashboard availability toggle, counsellor availability editor, admin counsellor management (`/admin/counsellors`), **student resource reads** (`/student/resources`, detail, dashboard recommended strip), **admin/counsellor resource CMS** (`/admin/resources/*`, `/counsellor/resources/*` — `src/api/resources.js`), **admin session log + dashboard KPIs**, and **landing carousel + public stats** (`src/api/public.js`). `ResourcesContext` is activity-feed stubs only; CMS data is API-backed.

Strathmore email validation remains on the frontend. Admin dashboard `platformHealth` / satisfaction ring remain mock (no DB). Analytics charts, counsellor performance, reports, and `last_active_at` on login are API-driven (Prompt 11). Account-requests queue, admin students directory, and platform notifications are API-driven (Prompt 10).

### Test Logins

Use backend-seeded accounts (see `backend/scripts/seed_*.py`), e.g.:

```text
student@strathmore.edu / counsellor@strathmore.edu — password from seed script
```

Legacy mock-only test accounts in `mockUsers.js` are no longer used for login when the API is reachable.

### Account Lifecycle

All new users register as **students**.

There is no public counsellor signup flow.

There is no public admin signup flow.

A counsellor account is created when an administrator promotes an existing student account to the `counsellor` role. Promotion also sets `isVerified: true` on the backend — newly promoted counsellors go straight to `/counsellor`. `/pending-approval` is only for legacy unverified counsellor rows, not the normal post-promotion path.

An admin account can only exist as a predefined system account in this frontend demo.

### Signup Rules

Students may sign up using a Strathmore University email address.

Valid signup email format:

```text
@strathmore.edu
```

If the email does not end with `@strathmore.edu`, display the inline error:

```text
Please use your Strathmore University email address.
```

Display the error directly beneath the email field.

Do not silently fail validation.

New signups should create a mock user with:

```js
{
  role: "student",
  isVerified: true
}
```

### Test Logins

Student:

```text
student@strathmore.edu
123456
```

Redirect:

```text
/student
```

Counsellor:

```text
counsellor@strathmore.edu
123456
```

Redirect:

```text
/counsellor
```

Admin:

```text
admin@strathmore.edu
123456
```

Redirect:

```text
/admin
```

### Email Rules

PeerPoint is restricted to members of the Strathmore University community.

All accounts in the system must use:

```text
@strathmore.edu
```

This applies to:

* Students
* Peer Counsellors
* Administrators

Any other email domain should be rejected with an inline validation error.

Error message:

```text
Please use your Strathmore University email address.
```

These test accounts exist only for frontend routing and demonstration purposes.

They do not imply public signup paths for counsellors or administrators.

### Route Behaviour

Unauthenticated users:

```text
Landing
Login
Signup
```

Authenticated students:

```text
/student
```

Authenticated counsellors:

```text
/counsellor
```

Authenticated admins:

```text
/admin
```

Role-based routing should be enforced through the existing mock authentication flow.

Signup validation: email must end in `@strathmore.edu` for both student and counsellor signup. If not, show an inline error: "Please use your Strathmore University email address." Do not block on this silently — show the message under the email field.

## Mock Data
Keep schemas generic and simple for now — they are NOT meant to mirror the production database schema yet (that'll be aligned later once the backend is finalized). Just enough shape to make the dashboards look realistic: counsellor profiles (bio, specialties, availability), sessions, pending requests, recent activity, platform stats.

## Output Rules
No TODOs. No omitted files. No placeholder comments like `// add logic here`. Every file must be complete and runnable as written.
